    <p> Sam decided to continue towards Queenstown and I towards Mount Cook. The route to the Mount Cook drove quite easily through layers and valleys and thanks to a good audio book, the time went around there very quickly. When I arrived at Mount Cook, I drove to the tourist information after the weather. Since there should be frost at night and wind up to 130km/h, I decided to drive 20km back and spend the night on a protected campsite with electricity for heating and hot water to shower. Well, the showers were a bit miserably low. I was able to look at the cabin separation without worrying at the top and wash my hair. The outlook on Mount Cook the next morning should compensate for a lot. But more about that later. </p>
